---
title: "Imported currency fields from Excel have incorrect values"
date: 2014-10-17T03:52:38.000Z
link: "https://community.servicenow.com/community?id=community_blog&sys_id=b34da229dbd0dbc01dcaf3231f9619ea"
---
<p>If you are having issues importing the correct values from Excel, you can make some quick adjustments to your currency field types to fix this. For example, when you go to your loaded table, you may find that your original cost value of <strong>12423453.43</strong> has dwarfed down to <strong>1.24</strong>:</p><p style="min-height: 8pt; height: 8pt; padding: 0px;">  </p><p><a _jive_internal="true" href="/servlet/JiveServlet/showImage/38-3554-14709/Screen Shot 2014-10-16 at 3.18.38 PM.JPG"><img  alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-16 at 3.18.38 PM.JPG" class="image-1 jive-image" height="109" src="6a0b8ccedbd81344e9737a9e0f9619bd.iix" style="height: 75px; width: 620px;" width="902"/></a></p><p><br/>Why is this happening? For one thing, currency fields are imported as decimal, <span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">which can sometimes cause large currency values to get corrupted if your columns or field types are not set up properly. There are a couple ways you can fix this: </span></p><ul><li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">You can change the column type in the Excel spreadsheet from <strong>Currency</strong> to <strong>Number</strong> before importing your file. </span></li><li><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Or, the preferred method, you can change the <strong>Cost</strong> field type in your record to <strong>Currency</strong>. The currency field is essentially a decimal field with two digits after the decimal point, which will get you back to the value you want. And, you'll only have to do this once as opposed to changing the column type every time you need to import. </span></li></ul><p style="min-height: 8pt; height: 8pt; padding: 0px;">  </p><h2><span style="font-size: 12pt;">To change your field type to Currency:</span></h2><ol><li>Open the loaded data record.</li><li>Under the <strong>Row</strong> header, click <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>0</strong></span>.</li><li>Right-click the <strong>Cost</strong> field, and select <strong>Personalize Dictionary</strong>.</li><li>In the <strong>Type</strong> field, enter <strong>Currency.</strong></li><li>Click <strong>Update</strong> and then <strong>OK</strong> to confirm changes.</li></ol><p><a _jive_internal="true" href="/servlet/JiveServlet/showImage/38-3554-14740/Screen Shot 2014-10-16 at 7.07.18 PM.JPG"><img  alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-16 at 7.07.18 PM.JPG" class="image-0 jive-image" height="594" src="9148ab7ddb9493049c9ffb651f961952.iix" style="height: 230px; width: 620px;" width="1600"/></a></p><p style="min-height: 8pt; height: 8pt; padding: 0px;">  </p><p>If you re-import your Excel data, you should now see that the<strong> Cost</strong> field has the correct currency value:</p><p><br/><a href="data:image/png;base64,"><img alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></a></p><p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;"><br/></span></p><p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">For more information, see:</span></p><p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;"><br/></span></p><p><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;"><br/></span></p>
